term_inventory_greek.meaning:
wrath, anger, the feeling and expression of strong displeasure and hostility;
this can range from petty human anger to the righteous anger of God toward sinful disobedience;
primarily mental bent, impulse;
anger, indignation, wrath, Eph. 4:31; Col. 3:8;
vengeance, punishment, Mt. 3:7; Lk. 3:7; 21:23; Rom. 13:4, 5

(middle/passive) to be angry, enraged, to feel and express strong displeasure and hostility;
this can range from petty human anger to the righteous anger of God toward sinful disobedience;
some list as deponent, ὀργιζομαι, to provoke to anger, irritate;
passive to be angry, indignant, enraged, Mt. 5:22; 18:34

wrath, fury, anger, rage, a state of intense displeasure based in some real or perceived wrong;
primarily the soul, mind; hence, a strong passion or emotion of the mind;
anger, wrath, rage Lk. 4:28; Acts 19:28; plural swellings of anger, 2Cor. 12:20; Gal. 5:20

(intr.) to be greatly distressed;
to be angered, irritated, provoke;
to sharpen; metaphorically to incite, stir up, Acts 17:16;
to irritate, provoke, anger 1Cor. 13:5
